        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3142170182" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer776895732101378645">Had I known at the time that ‚Äúmistakes were often as revealing as the right answer‚Äù and I probably wouldn‚Äôt have been such a lousy maths student. Well, to be fair I was beyond lousy. I was literally a numerical disaster waiting to happen. I can still remember the teacher‚Äôs face after I had given an answer to a problem as if it happened yesterday. I can still feel my face burning the way it did every time I was called to the blackboard to solve an equation. <br/><br/>Till this day I honestly don‚Äôt know if </span>
  <span id="freeText776895732101378645" style="display:none">Had I known at the time that ‚Äúmistakes were often as revealing as the right answer‚Äù and I probably wouldn‚Äôt have been such a lousy maths student. Well, to be fair I was beyond lousy. I was literally a numerical disaster waiting to happen. I can still remember the teacher‚Äôs face after I had given an answer to a problem as if it happened yesterday. I can still feel my face burning the way it did every time I was called to the blackboard to solve an equation. <br /><br />Till this day I honestly don‚Äôt know if I was really that bad or if my disastrous results were due to pure boredom or even laziness. Maybe both. But the truth is that I hated it. Everything; numbers, equations, formulas... Bahh!!!<br /><br />And then, after all these years I‚Äôve read this original and gentle little novel and I wish had payed more attention to the beauty behind numbers. <br />I don‚Äôt know how Ogawa does this, but she can literally show me beauty and harmony everywhere and in everything. Even numbers.<br />And her prose, oh my goodness, what a joy to read; Gourmet treats for the brain, literally.<br /><br />On the surface there‚Äôs not a lot happening in this little gem. It‚Äòs a really simple story about friendship told in a very tender way. The magic is there behind numbers and letters, as it is behind everything else, but only for the ones who really want to see it. <br /><br />I loved it, and the four star rating is only a reflection of my enjoyment when compared to Ogawa‚Äôs <i>The Memory Police</i>. <br /><br />What a beauty of a novel!!! <br /><br />‚Äú(...) there was no shame in admitting you didn‚Äôt have the answer, it was a necessary step toward the truth.‚Äù</span>
